04:12.059 --> 04:19.607
So, as I said today, we are going to be taking the fourth topic in the series and that is on wisdom.

04:20.108 --> 04:25.874
And hopefully what we'll do is look at some examples from the Book of Daniel of what we can learn about

04:25.954 --> 04:28.498
what godly wisdom is and how we can apply that to our lives.

04:30.261 --> 04:32.264
So the first question is what is wisdom?

04:32.905 --> 04:35.550
And I spent a long time looking for definitions of wisdom.

04:35.590 --> 04:38.795
So you'll forgive me because the best definition I could find was from Wikipedia.

04:39.636 --> 04:48.791
So Wikipedia defines wisdom as the ability to apply knowledge, experience and good judgment to navigate life's complexities.

04:49.372 --> 04:50.674
So essentially it's

04:50.786 --> 04:58.660
knowing things, having lived things, experiencing things and then taking all of that and applying it to the situations that we face.

04:59.642 --> 05:01.485
And that's very different to knowledge.

05:01.605 --> 05:04.230
Knowledge is factual, it's information.

05:05.292 --> 05:13.507
Whereas wisdom is about the application of that because it's possible to have a lot of knowledge, it's possible to know a lot of things without actually being wise.

05:14.909 --> 05:15.250
It's

05:15.842 --> 05:22.810
possible to acquire vast amounts of information without knowing how to actually apply it, how to actually make it useful for our lives.

05:23.411 --> 05:30.399
And there's like a funny quote which you've probably seen before, which says that knowledge is known that a tomato is a fruit, but wisdom is known not to put it in a fruit salad.

05:30.839 --> 05:33.122
So knowledge and wisdom, very different things.

05:34.303 --> 05:37.727
But then I found what I think is a better definition of wisdom.

05:37.767 --> 05:40.370
And this was from the NIBBiable.com.

05:40.994 --> 05:47.600
And it said that wisdom is a capacity of mind that allows us to understand life from God's perspective.

05:49.342 --> 06:09.681
And I think it's such a good definition because where we see the Wikipedia definition of a wisdom as being about our knowledge and our experiences and how we apply them to life, or even the knowledge and experiences of our fellow man, even the collective knowledge and wisdom of all of mankind.

06:10.021 --> 06:10.962
And that is

06:11.170 --> 06:16.782
That's helpful, that's useful, but ultimately it's still limited and ultimately it's still flawed.

06:17.767 --> 06:18.290
Where is

06:18.338 --> 06:20.420
Godly wisdom stems from God.

06:20.860 --> 06:26.125
It stems from the infinite knowledge and infinite wisdom of the person who made the heavens and the earth.

06:26.825 --> 06:28.607
And all of that is accessible to us.

06:28.987 --> 06:31.569
He knows all things because he made all things.

06:31.670 --> 06:36.173
He knows what is right and what is wrong because he defined what is right and what is wrong.

06:37.114 --> 06:46.963
And the fact that we have access to his mind, the fact that we have access to all of the wisdom that he supplies is not something that we should underestimate.

06:47.063 --> 06:48.324
And it's all there for us.

06:48.304 --> 06:51.395
there for us in the Word of God, we just have to access it.

06:52.298 --> 06:57.938
We should never underestimate how precious and how valuable that is.

06:58.722 --> 07:01.747
What can we learn about godly wisdom from the Book of Daniel?

07:01.787 --> 07:03.970
Well, we're gonna be focusing on Daniel chapter two.

07:04.611 --> 07:15.208
And if I just set the scene and put it into context, we know that the Book of Daniel is set in a time when the Israelite people had been taken into captivity by the kingdom of Babylon.

07:15.849 --> 07:24.242
And Daniel alongside a number of the young men had been selected to be in service to the king who at what time was Nebuchadnezzar.

07:24.834 --> 07:32.903
And in Daniel chapter two, which tells us that one night, King Nebuchadnezzar had a dream that was very confusing and very troubling.

07:33.784 --> 07:37.308
And when he walked, he wanted to understand what the dream meant.

07:37.768 --> 07:43.795
And so he called for various people in his kingdom, the wise people in his kingdom.

07:43.815 --> 07:53.586
So the magicians, the astrologers, the sorcerers, the mathematicians, basically anyone in the kingdom who might have the ability to be able to interpret his dream for him.

07:54.594 --> 08:03.407
Now, you might recall that there's a similar event that was recorded in Scripture and that was with Pharaoh in the time of Joseph when he also had a dream.

08:04.128 --> 08:07.392
And he called his wise men to interpret it for him.

08:07.693 --> 08:16.906
But Nebuchadnezzar did something slightly different, which I think is hilariously unreasonable, which is that he refused to even say what his dream was.

08:17.407 --> 08:22.514
He said, I need you to tell me what my dream is and then interpret it for me.

08:22.978 --> 08:26.804
So, so the wise men obviously said to him, like, this is, this is not possible.

08:26.924 --> 08:29.909
It's, it isn't possible to do what you're asking.

08:29.969 --> 08:33.535
There isn't a man in this kingdom who can tell you what your dream is.

08:33.575 --> 08:36.820
Just tell us the dream and then we will attempt to interpret it.

08:36.880 --> 08:39.945
But King Nebuchadnezzar said, no, I've made my decision.

08:39.985 --> 08:43.410
You need to.

08:43.586 --> 08:45.048
you need to tell me what my dream is.

08:45.568 --> 08:52.416
And because they couldn't do this, and in his fury, he set out a decree that all the wise men in the entire kingdom were gonna be destroyed.

08:52.796 --> 08:58.222
And he sent his guards out to find and kill them all, which was pretty extreme.

08:59.003 --> 09:04.208
But sadly, that included Daniel and his companions because they were amongst the learned and wise in the kingdom.

09:05.089 --> 09:05.950
So that's the context.

09:06.691 --> 09:13.298
So I'm gonna read a couple of verses from Daniel chapter two, and it's verses 14 to 20, and then verse 23.

09:14.850 --> 09:24.604
So it says, when Ariok, the commander of the king's guard, had gone out to put to death the wise men of Babylon, Daniel spoke to him with wisdom and tact.

09:25.185 --> 09:29.311
He asked the king's officer, why did the king issues such a harsh decree?

09:30.293 --> 09:32.135
Ariok then explained the matter to Daniel.

09:32.877 --> 09:37.583
At this, Daniel went into the king and asked for time so that he might interpret the dream for him.

09:38.685 --> 09:44.754
Then Daniel returned to his house and explained the matter to his friends, Hananiah, Michelle, and Azariah.

09:44.866 --> 09:56.087
He urged them to plead for mercy from the God of Heaven concerning this mystery so that he and his friends might not be executed with the rest of the wise men of Babylon.

09:57.170 --> 09:59.815
During the night, the mystery was revealed to Daniel in a vision.

09:59.875 --> 10:07.890
Then Daniel praised the God of Heaven and said, praise be to the name of God forever and ever, wisdom and power are his.

10:08.290 --> 10:12.763
I thank and praise you, God of my ancestors, you have given me wisdom and power.

10:13.164 --> 10:17.517
You have made known to me what we asked of you, and you have made known to us the dream of the king.

10:17.557 --> 10:20.466
And then if you

10:20.930 --> 10:39.910
continue to read on to the rest of the chapter, then you'll see that Daniel was granted an ordinance with the king, he glorified God, and then he was not only able to recount the king's dream as requested, but he also gave him the interpretation and in soldiering he and his friends found favor with the king and their lives were preserved.

10:40.451 --> 10:41.874
So that's the context.

10:42.338 --> 10:46.164
So what can we take from this account and what can we learn about Godly wisdom?

10:46.224 --> 10:51.873
Well, there's lots of things, but there was four things in particular that I wanted to highlight.

10:52.975 --> 11:00.306
So the first thing is that Godly wisdom is proactive without being reactive.

11:01.538 --> 11:05.788
So Daniel calmly sought out information to better understand his situation.

11:06.690 --> 11:11.160
So if we read verses 14 and 15 again, it says that Daniel spoke to him with wisdom intact.

11:11.180 --> 11:15.390
He asked the king's officer, why did the king issue such a harsh decree?

11:15.410 --> 11:20.882
So we can probably agree that Daniel's situation was was pretty.

11:21.250 --> 11:22.031
was pretty desperate.

11:22.572 --> 11:26.820
This decree had gone out that the wise men in the land were going to be killed.

11:27.401 --> 11:30.927
And Daniel was unlikely to have been the first person to have been approached.

11:30.967 --> 11:37.599
He may well have already heard of people that he knew, people that he had been educated with having already been killed.

11:38.360 --> 11:46.194
And it would be understandable for him to be a bit alarmed and to panic and to be really quite worried about his own situation.

11:46.658 --> 11:56.908
But what Daniel didn't do was wail and lament and say, woe is me and how could God bring me into captivity and preserve my life only to have me killed.

11:56.948 --> 12:02.634
What he did do was take a moment to understand his situation.

12:02.674 --> 12:08.900
He calmly and proactively gathered the information that he needed to be able to plan his next steps.

12:08.920 --> 12:10.702
He simply asked a question of the king's officer.

12:11.283 --> 12:12.744
Why did the king issue this decree?

12:12.905 --> 12:14.386
And the officer answered him.

12:15.106 --> 12:16.187
But why is that important?

12:16.628 --> 12:17.649
Well, two things.

12:18.270 --> 12:23.736
Firstly, acting without reacting demonstrates our faith in both the goodness and the power of God.

12:24.256 --> 12:26.378
It says that, yes, my situation is difficult.

12:26.459 --> 12:28.781
That's not denying that I'm in a bind.

12:29.061 --> 12:29.882
This is difficult.

12:30.443 --> 12:32.265
But I know that God loves me.

12:33.266 --> 12:37.291
I know that he's on my side and I know that he has the power to intervene.

12:37.331 --> 12:44.018
When we act without reacting, it's evidence that we actually trust God above all else.

12:45.410 --> 12:58.810
And secondly, where panic can cloud our minds and prevent us from seeing the way forward, acting without reacting, it quiets our spirit and it leaves us open to actually receive instruction and practical guidance from God.

13:00.412 --> 13:10.066
Now, when you look through scripture, there are lots of examples of when God's people have found themselves in quite alarming situations.

13:10.146 --> 13:22.886
And unfortunately, you haven't always necessarily demonstrated that godly wisdom, despite having ample evidence of God's love for them and evidence of his power that's been demonstrated to them personally in the past.

13:23.387 --> 13:32.281
And a couple of examples of that, or one example is of the Israelites when they had just been released from captivity in Egypt.

13:33.222 --> 13:38.290
They had been rescued and they were on their way to the lands that God had promised them.

13:38.754 --> 13:41.819
they reached the edge of the Red Sea with apparently no way forward.

13:42.200 --> 13:47.028
And then to make it worse, Pharaoh had changed his mind and he was giving chase and they were trapped in the middle.

13:48.030 --> 13:55.623
Now, we have to remember that the people had just witnessed and experienced a miraculous rescue from Egypt.

13:55.984 --> 14:04.178
They had just witnessed the 10 plagues where God's power and authority had been clearly demonstrated and

14:04.258 --> 14:08.287
they had been saved and they had been promised that they were going to see the promised land.

14:09.810 --> 14:20.914
So when they encountered this setback, they knew what God had already done and they knew what God had promised to do, but they panicked and they reacted.

14:21.378 --> 14:28.048
And if you read Exodus 14, verse 11 to 12, they cried out to Moses and they said, why did you bring us out here in the wilderness to die?

14:28.088 --> 14:30.331
Weren't there enough graves for us in Egypt?

14:30.832 --> 14:32.615
Didn't we tell you that this was going to happen?

14:32.935 --> 14:36.541
It would have been better for us to serve the Egyptians than to die in the wilderness.

14:36.941 --> 14:40.146
So they definitely didn't approach things with a cool head.

14:40.834 --> 14:44.302
And another example of this is Jesus-owned disciples.

14:45.665 --> 14:55.026
One situation that they encountered was when they were in the boat with Jesus at night and Jesus was sleeping and then they encountered a raging storm.

14:55.138 --> 15:05.775
Again, the disciples, they had seen Jesus turn water into wine and they had seen him heal sick and give sight to the blind and all manner of other miracles.

15:05.815 --> 15:10.062
They knew and believed that he was the son of God and they knew what he could do.

15:11.344 --> 15:13.568
But when they were in that situation, they panicked.

15:13.968 --> 15:17.354
They woke Jesus up and they cried, don't you even care if we all die?

15:17.374 --> 15:19.858
And I think, you know, we

15:19.938 --> 15:21.220
We can relate to that.

15:21.240 --> 15:26.230
We can look at that and think, oh, these are the lights, these disciples.

15:26.530 --> 15:28.774
But the reality is that we all do that.

15:29.716 --> 15:33.824
We find ourselves in difficult situations and we think what is going on.

15:33.904 --> 15:36.388
And we worry and we panic and we stress.

15:38.492 --> 15:41.618
But the reality is that setbacks are a part of life.

15:41.922 --> 15:42.643
they're gonna happen.

15:43.363 --> 15:49.729
They aren't pleasant and they do try to shake us, but the evidence of godly wisdom is not the absence of setbacks.

15:49.869 --> 15:56.756
It's not making all the right decisions so that we never find ourselves in a difficult situation because that just isn't in our power.

15:56.816 --> 16:02.161
The evidence of godly wisdom is how we respond when they inevitably occur.

16:03.122 --> 16:11.730
Do we panic and complain or do we use that setback as an opportunity to demonstrate how much we trust God and allow him to actually show up on our behalf

16:12.514 --> 16:22.124
Because if we look at those two examples, you know, the Israelites that are set back on the edge of the Red Sea, that paved the way for one of the most amazing miracles that's recorded in scripture, the potting of the Red Sea.

16:23.165 --> 16:31.133
And for the disciples in the boat, they got to see Jesus demonstrate his authority even over the natural world.

16:31.534 --> 16:39.282
You know, it paved the way for God to show his power in amazing ways that just needed to trust God.

16:39.906 --> 16:43.289
So godly wisdom is in acting without reacting.

16:46.272 --> 16:52.398
The second thing that I wanted to mention is that godly wisdom doesn't try to go it alone.

16:53.399 --> 16:57.163
So Daniel sought out support from godly companions.

16:59.265 --> 17:08.594
So in verse 17, it tells us that Daniel, then Daniel returned to his house and explained the matter to his friends, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah.

17:10.242 --> 17:12.885
We all need godly companions to do life with.

17:13.345 --> 17:13.886
We need them.

17:14.667 --> 17:15.508
No man is an island.

17:16.469 --> 17:19.952
None of us were intended to walk through life alone.

17:19.993 --> 17:36.210
And there are times that even with all the knowledge and all the understanding and all the faith and all the evidence of what God has done, sometimes we just need a support and the Council of

17:36.514 --> 17:37.575
of others, friends.

17:37.615 --> 17:41.240
There were times when it's just not wise to go through things alone.

17:41.260 --> 17:48.469
And we see from scripture right from the creation of man that God, you know, man was never meant to be alone.

17:48.509 --> 17:51.753
God designed man and said, this is perfect.

17:51.833 --> 17:52.433
This is good.

17:53.094 --> 17:55.217
But aloneness was considered to be bad.

17:55.717 --> 18:01.244
If you look at the account in Genesis, the only thing that God described as not good was man being alone.

18:01.264 --> 18:02.866
And

18:04.002 --> 18:13.295
It's really important for us to strike the balance because what we don't want to do is be in a situation where we are utterly dependent on others to lift us up.

18:13.756 --> 18:16.740
You know, we need to have a personal relationship with God.

18:16.820 --> 18:29.618
We need to have a personal conviction of who God is to us and an understanding of what he can do and be confident in that ourselves.

18:30.050 --> 18:34.498
our faith is deeply personal and nobody can cultivate that relationship with God for us.

18:34.899 --> 18:42.012
But that doesn't change the fact that sometimes we need other people because there are times when the burdens are too heavy for us to bear alone.

18:43.835 --> 18:46.059
But what is it that stops us from doing that?

18:46.099 --> 18:54.034
Well, sometimes we may have been hurt or let down by people in the past and we know that those wounds can be difficult to heal.

18:54.690 --> 18:56.992
Sometimes it's our own personal pride.

18:58.133 --> 19:02.558
That stops us from sharing our problems because we are afraid to appear weak.

19:02.698 --> 19:06.962
We are afraid to appear as if we don't have it all together.

19:08.324 --> 19:11.247
But seeking the support of others is not a sign of weakness.

19:11.707 --> 19:13.329
It's a demonstration of godly wisdom.

19:13.349 --> 19:22.578
Ecclesiastes 4 and verses 9 to 10 says, two are better than one.

19:23.138 --> 19:25.461
because they have a good return for their labour.

19:25.501 --> 19:33.931
If either of them falls down, one can help the other up, but pity anyone who falls and has no one to help them up.

19:35.232 --> 19:40.358
So the reality is that no matter how strong our faith, sometimes we will fall down.

19:40.739 --> 19:43.762
We will face trials and challenges that are too much for us to bear alone.

19:44.123 --> 19:47.026
And as we select the start, that's just simply the reality of life.

19:47.202 --> 19:49.364
There is a danger in isolating ourselves.

19:50.045 --> 19:58.034
We can find ourselves lulled into a false sense of security, thinking that we're better off or that we don't need others.

19:58.575 --> 20:00.457
And that might be the case for a while.

20:00.537 --> 20:02.099
We might be fine for a time.

20:02.459 --> 20:15.474
And if we're in a season where we're costing, where actually things are OK and nothing is particularly difficult, then we can deceive ourselves into thinking that actually I'm actually fine on my own.

20:15.714 --> 20:18.827
The reality is that when danger strikes, isolation makes us vulnerable.

20:18.847 --> 20:25.074
Now, a couple of months ago, Pulumi gave an example from scripture, which

20:25.154 --> 20:29.981
I think I've successfully managed to mention in every single time I've been up on here since then.

20:30.021 --> 20:32.725
And I'm going to mention it again and I make no apologies because it's really, really good.

20:33.786 --> 20:43.339
But it's in the big of judges and it talks about a time called a town, sorry called Fleish, and that was targeted to partake over by the Israelites.

20:43.820 --> 20:50.930
And if we look at the account in Judges chapter 18 and verse 78, what it says about this town, it says,

20:51.362 --> 20:58.792
So the five men left and came to Laish where they saw that the people were living in safety, like the Sidonians, at peace and secure.

20:59.433 --> 21:02.156
And since their land lacked nothing, they were prosperous.

21:03.238 --> 21:05.781
So this town of Laish was doing really well.

21:06.282 --> 21:07.303
It had everything it needed.

21:07.323 --> 21:08.605
It was prospering.

21:08.625 --> 21:09.406
They were costing.

21:10.007 --> 21:11.829
They didn't need anything from anyone.

21:12.370 --> 21:14.252
But they had no idea that they were being watched.

21:14.333 --> 21:16.015
They had no idea that they were a target.

21:16.916 --> 21:18.418
And while they

21:18.754 --> 21:21.578
appeared to be doing well and going about their daily lives.

21:21.598 --> 21:24.603
They actually had no idea how vulnerable they really were.

21:24.643 --> 21:32.395
And when you continue on in that chapter, Judges 18 and into verses 27 and 28, it tells us what happened to this town.

21:32.956 --> 21:37.123
It says, they attacked them with the sword and burned down their city.

21:37.163 --> 21:44.274
And there was no one to rescue them because they lived a long way from Sidon and had no relationship with anyone else.

21:45.538 --> 21:49.482
We need to let that be a warning to us that we can be doing okay.

21:50.043 --> 21:51.004
We can be costing.

21:51.124 --> 21:53.587
We can be prospering on the surface of it.

21:53.727 --> 22:01.076
But when we're alone, when we're isolated, we are vulnerable because when those attacks come, we've got no one to rescue us.

22:03.779 --> 22:08.064
First Peter five and verse eight warns us, be alert of sober mind.

22:09.085 --> 22:13.810
Your enemy, the devil prowls around like a roaring lion looking for someone to devour.

22:15.650 --> 22:23.123
And I was thinking about, you know, my kids and I, we watched probably a lot of people do watch the David Attenborough documentary, Our Planet, which you talk about the natural world.

22:23.344 --> 22:31.919
And time and time again, you see the lions or the cheaters or the jaguars when they are on the hunt.

22:32.360 --> 22:40.114
They don't attack the animal that's in the middle of the herd because the herd is impenetrable.

22:40.418 --> 22:48.427
even with their speed and their strength and their teeth, they cannot overcome the collective strength of the herd.

22:48.847 --> 22:49.768
And so what do they do?

22:49.829 --> 22:56.276
They target the loner, they target the animal that wasn't quite paying attention and has wandered off alone.

22:56.336 --> 23:01.161
The isolation of those animals makes them vulnerable and it's no different for us.

23:01.442 --> 23:02.663
We need to be wise.

23:02.703 --> 23:05.426
We can't make ourselves easy targets.

23:07.010 --> 23:11.938
But as well as avoiding isolation, the choice of companionship is also really important.

23:12.519 --> 23:21.334
And godly wisdom dictates that we should find godly allies to do life with, because ungodly ones can send us in a direction that we don't want to go in.

23:22.215 --> 23:30.108
And scripture gives us lots of verses that talk about the benefits and the dangers of the type of companionship that we hold.

23:30.649 --> 23:33.554
I've put a couple of verses up there.

23:33.634 --> 23:37.439
Proverbs 27 verse 17 tells us that iron sharpens iron.

23:37.759 --> 23:41.925
So in other words, godly relationships, they make both parties sharper, stronger, wiser.

23:41.945 --> 23:50.095
Proverbs 13 verse 20 says, whoever walks with the wise becomes wise, but the companion of fools will suffer harm.

23:51.056 --> 23:58.706
Proverbs 18, 24, one who has unreliable friends soon comes to ruin, but there is a friend who sticks closer than a brother.

23:59.170 --> 24:02.013
And first Corinthians 1533, did not be misled.

24:02.073 --> 24:04.155
Bad company corrupts a good character.

24:04.796 --> 24:07.578
The only thing that is worse than isolation is bad companionship.

24:10.601 --> 24:15.827
In a time of trouble and danger, Daniel sought out not just any friends, but true godly companions.

24:16.587 --> 24:18.850
And so like Daniel, we need to do the same.

24:18.890 --> 24:22.073
We need to cultivate strong godly relationships.

24:22.133 --> 24:27.218
And these relationships, they take time and effort to cultivate.

24:27.522 --> 24:47.064
sometimes think it's so much easier for children to just make friends that thrown into a situation like like kids or school where they're automatically surrounded by people who are of the same age as them and have similar interests and it's so much harder as an adult and I think it just gets more and more complicated as life goes on.

24:47.084 --> 24:55.634
I was thinking about myself and you know I miss my maternity leave days where I could just ring up a friend and say let's go for a coffee and we just

24:56.034 --> 25:01.586
we just thought, it just happened whereas now I'm penciling people into the third.

25:01.890 --> 25:05.393
Wednesday of September and, you know, subject to availability.

25:05.473 --> 25:07.835
And the reality is it's just, it's hard.

25:08.636 --> 25:11.378
It's difficult to make time, but it's worth it.

25:11.598 --> 25:12.659
It's worth the effort.

25:13.180 --> 25:17.964
And I see myself, I go through seasons where I'm just so busy.

25:18.064 --> 25:18.745
I'm just so busy.

25:19.085 --> 25:19.946
I don't see anybody.

25:19.986 --> 25:23.108
I see people at work and I see people in church, but I don't see anybody.

25:23.549 --> 25:26.651
And then I go through other times when I think, no, I'm going to be really intentional.

25:26.672 --> 25:28.593
I'm going to make time for people.

25:28.953 --> 25:31.876
And the difference is obvious.

25:31.856 --> 25:34.921
we need to cultivate those friendships.

25:35.062 --> 25:42.915
And so I would just encourage anybody who is feeling like they want to cultivate those godly friendships, but don't know where to start.

25:44.117 --> 25:45.920
Don't try and do that alone.

25:45.960 --> 25:46.962
Ask for help.

25:47.522 --> 25:50.226
Ask David, ask Nicola, ask any of the leaders in the church.

25:50.506 --> 25:56.816
If you're thinking about joining a life group and you don't know where to start, ask for help in choosing one that would work for you.

25:56.856 --> 26:04.767
Don't be afraid or too shy to help but to ask for help because godly wisdom is in seeking support from godly companions.

26:04.868 --> 26:05.869
It's so important.

26:09.054 --> 26:14.642
The third thing is that godly wisdom seeks counsel from god and we can see that Daniel prayed.

26:15.490 --> 26:22.063
Verse 18 tells us that he urged them to plead for mercy from the God of heaven concerning this mystery.

26:22.945 --> 26:26.011
So in a time of danger, Daniel sought God in prayer.

26:26.532 --> 26:29.257
And we'll notice that prayer wasn't the last resort.

26:29.979 --> 26:34.147
It wasn't, I'm going to make this plan and we're going to try this and we're going to do this.

26:34.187 --> 26:37.874
And if all else feels, well, at least we can still pray.

26:38.210 --> 26:43.238
When Daniel sought out his companions, the first thing that they did was seek the face of God.

26:43.278 --> 26:45.261
The first thing that they did was to pray.

26:46.002 --> 26:55.517
And it's so important that we put things in their proper place because we can sometimes try to be completely self-sufficient and just be problem solvers.

26:55.617 --> 26:58.121
And there's nothing wrong with thinking about things.

26:58.161 --> 27:01.326
There's nothing wrong with being, we've talked about being proactive.

27:03.249 --> 27:06.354
But what we don't want to do is

27:07.202 --> 27:13.498
We don't want to make our plans and then present them to God for verification and approval.

27:15.463 --> 27:17.549
We also don't want him to be the last resort.

27:18.030 --> 27:20.396
God wants us to seek him first.

27:21.018 --> 27:22.642
He wants to be first.

27:23.074 --> 27:29.021
Proverbs three verses five to six says, trust in the Lord with all your heart and do not depend on your own understanding.

27:29.742 --> 27:33.547
Seekers will in all you do and he will show you which path to take.

27:33.727 --> 27:39.134
He is going to set us in the right direction because there are a multitude of ways to solve a problem.

27:39.474 --> 27:46.002
But when we seek the face of God first, he sets us on the right path so that we don't waste time going down the wrong one.

27:47.842 --> 27:51.848
When we come to God first, we open ourselves to receiving his wisdom and his guidance.

27:51.868 --> 27:54.952
And as we said before, it quiets our spirit.

27:55.553 --> 28:04.826
It blocks out the anxious thoughts and the plans that arise from our own limited understanding and opens us up to receiving what God wants to direct us in.

28:04.886 --> 28:16.242
Philippians chapter four verse six says, don't be anxious about anything, but in every situation by prayer and petition with thanksgiving, present your requests to God.

28:16.738 --> 28:23.344
And the consequence of doing that, it says, is that the peace of God which transcends all understanding will guard your hearts and your minds in Christ Jesus.

28:24.485 --> 28:36.937
When we act without praying, we often make unwise decisions out of fear and limited understanding, but when we prioritize prayer, it paves the way for peace, for clarity, and just good decision making.

28:37.738 --> 28:39.479
So Godly wisdom seeks God's counsel.

28:42.202 --> 28:46.546
And then the fourth is that Godly wisdom demonstrates gratitude.

28:47.394 --> 28:48.396
Daniel gave thanks.

28:49.999 --> 28:55.007
So verses 19 and 23, it says, and Daniel prays the God of heaven.

28:55.047 --> 28:58.293
It says, I thank and I praise you, God of my ancestors.

28:58.674 --> 29:00.417
You have given me wisdom and power.

29:00.717 --> 29:02.881
You have made known to me what we asked of you.

29:02.901 --> 29:05.365
You have made known to us the dream of the king.

29:06.407 --> 29:08.891
There is godly wisdom in thanking God.

29:08.931 --> 29:12.818
And thankfulness is an active process.

29:13.602 --> 29:20.916
There's a pastor in Christian author called Tim Keller, and he said, it's one thing to be grateful, and it's another thing to give thanks.

29:21.457 --> 29:24.783
Gratitude is what you feel, but thanksgiving is what you do.

29:25.644 --> 29:31.295
And there are a number of Bible verses that talk about us being instructed to give thanks.

29:32.557 --> 29:35.122
And again, I've put a few examples up there.

29:35.746 --> 29:45.961
1 Thessalonians 5 verses 16 to 18, it says, the choice always, pray continually, give thanks in all circumstances, for this is God's will for you in Christ Jesus.

29:46.682 --> 29:51.770
Psalm 107 verse one, give thanks to the Lord, for he is good, his love and joyous forever.

29:51.810 --> 29:57.178
Psalm 100 verse four, enter his gates with thanksgiving in his courts with praise.

29:57.739 --> 29:59.641
Give thanks to him and praise his name.

29:59.702 --> 30:02.706
In Ephesians 5, 20,

30:02.786 --> 30:07.113
always giving thanks to God the Father for everything in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.

30:07.674 --> 30:09.717
And these are just a few examples.

30:09.737 --> 30:17.390
The scripture is full of examples of instructions and also examples of people actively giving thanks and praising God.

30:18.571 --> 30:20.014
So thankfulness is an active process.

30:20.074 --> 30:21.917
It's more than just a feeling like love.

30:22.358 --> 30:24.080
It requires demonstration.

30:25.843 --> 30:27.886
The account above doesn't say that Daniel was grateful.

30:27.906 --> 30:30.130
It says that he gave thanks

30:30.658 --> 30:33.883
Now it's obviously it's important that we feel gratitude in our hearts toward God.

30:34.684 --> 30:41.614
But then when we make a deliberate, active, outward expression of that gratitude, it has a multitude of benefits.

30:42.836 --> 30:44.038
So a couple of those things.

30:44.118 --> 30:47.683
Firstly, thankfulness, it glorifies God.

30:47.723 --> 30:52.470
That outward expression of our gratitude is an active worship to God.

30:52.530 --> 30:54.994
It's a demonstration that we

30:55.394 --> 30:58.638
ascribe all praise and all honor to him, the God most high.

30:58.678 --> 31:04.285
And we recognize him as the source of our blessings, of our peace, of our wisdom.

31:05.947 --> 31:09.671
The second is that it brings us closer to God when we're thankful.

31:10.332 --> 31:14.517
Psalm 22 verse three says that God inhabits the praises of his people.

31:15.078 --> 31:21.186
So when we actively praise and thank God it draws us closer to him and it builds our own personal relationship with him.

31:22.647 --> 31:24.850
And then the third is that when we're

31:25.122 --> 31:28.068
When we give thanks to God, it serves as a testimony to others.

31:28.629 --> 31:30.333
We're not keeping it to ourselves.

31:31.535 --> 31:34.862
Psalm 9 verse 1 says, I will give thanks to you, Lord, with all my heart.

31:35.083 --> 31:37.448
I will tell of all your wonderful deeds.

31:38.009 --> 31:42.418
So when we publicly thank God and, you know,

31:42.466 --> 31:47.052
openly give thanks to him for the things that he is doing and who he is to us.

31:47.433 --> 31:49.456
Then it serves as a testament to others.

31:49.496 --> 31:53.762
It allows them to celebrate with us and to rejoice with us over what God has done.

31:54.202 --> 31:56.666
But it also serves as an anchor for their own faith.

31:57.106 --> 31:59.790
Because we've said, there are things that we're all believing God for.

31:59.810 --> 32:01.332
There are things that we're all going through.

32:01.352 --> 32:06.680
And when we hear others giving thanks for what God has done in their lives, it boosts our own faith.

32:06.740 --> 32:08.542
And it reminds us that, yes, God is there.

32:08.622 --> 32:09.303
God can do it.

32:09.323 --> 32:10.105
God does do it.

32:10.165 --> 32:11.186
He loves us.

32:11.586 --> 32:15.051
And so we should never be shy to give thanks to God.

32:15.071 --> 32:19.478
There is wisdom in openly and actively giving thanks.

32:22.562 --> 32:30.514
So in summary, what we've said is that we can see from the Daniel chapter two and we can

32:31.074 --> 32:40.166
We can take from that that there is godly wisdom and acting without reacting, seeking support from godly companions, prioritising prayer and giving thanks to God.

32:40.867 --> 32:46.455
And we know that setbacks and challenges are inevitably going to occur in big and small ways as we go through life.

32:47.096 --> 32:49.519
But like Daniel, they don't have to shake us.

32:49.539 --> 32:51.922
They don't have to derail us.

32:52.194 --> 32:57.700
When we apply Godly wisdom to life setbacks, they provide opportunities for us to demonstrate our faith in God.

32:58.281 --> 33:01.545
And in his power and his love for us, it tells us that we know that God loves us.

33:02.626 --> 33:06.571
And they draw us closer to him and also serves as an encouragement to others.

33:07.612 --> 33:13.839
And we haven't been able to even scratch the surface of what scripture tells us about Godly wisdom.

33:13.859 --> 33:16.082
There's so much.

33:16.418 --> 33:21.083
It's if you just search the word wisdom, there's just a wealth in the scriptures about that.

33:21.624 --> 33:24.747
And it's something that we really need to invest time in studying for ourselves.

33:25.688 --> 33:38.783
But the last thing that I wanted to say as I invite Adam off, as we were going to a time of ministry is the fact that, you know, in Daniel's day, there were people that were considered to be the wise.

33:38.843 --> 33:44.850
There were those that were considered to be the learned and the educated and the keepers of wisdom.

33:44.962 --> 33:47.607
Wisdom isn't for a select view, it's for all of us.

33:48.508 --> 33:51.133
We all have access to the wisdom that God supplies.

33:52.535 --> 34:03.154
James 1 verse 5 says that if anyone lacks wisdom, anyone, you should ask God who gives generously to all without finding fault and it will be given to you.

34:03.746 --> 34:12.378
And I think, and I just want to emphasize without finding fault because, you know, it takes humility to go to God and to ask for wisdom to say, I don't have the answers.

34:12.438 --> 34:13.599
I don't have it figured out.

34:14.120 --> 34:14.781
I need help.

34:15.202 --> 34:17.565
I need you to set me on the right path.

34:18.526 --> 34:20.429
But when we do that, God doesn't refortress.

34:20.449 --> 34:24.274
He doesn't, you know, he doesn't belittle us.

34:24.354 --> 34:26.578
He doesn't say, why don't you already know this?

34:26.678 --> 34:28.060
How long have you been walking with me?

34:28.120 --> 34:30.925
How long have you had faith in me and you still need to ask?

34:30.945 --> 34:33.028
He doesn't do that.

34:33.529 --> 34:35.212
He invites us to come to him.

34:35.252 --> 34:38.117
He invites us to come freely to the throne of grace.

34:38.177 --> 34:39.679
He says, I have the wisdom.

34:39.739 --> 34:40.621
It's available to you.

34:40.761 --> 34:41.763
You just need to ask.

34:42.464 --> 34:51.058
And so I would encourage all of us that if we lack wisdom, if there's something that we need wisdom for, we should come to God freely and ask because He gives it to us freely.

